    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-09-29T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-09-29T09:00:00-05:00" n="216"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d216">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.3531/516: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Argentina</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Weddell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Buenos Aires</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-09-29T10:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 29, 1937—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 12:54 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>185. My 182 of September 24, 6 p.m. The Minister of Finance is apparently not yet
                    ready to discuss the matter with me, the delay as <pb facs="0226" n="216"
                        xml:id="pg_216"/> explained by the Under Secretary being due to the
                    Minister’s desire to have in hand data from various sources.</p>
                <p>However, yesterday afternoon I pressed the matter with the Minister for Foreign
                        Affairs<note n="6" xml:id="d216fn6">Carlos Saavedra Lamas.</note> who said
                    that he was sympathetic to my viewpoint and asked me to give him a brief
                    memorandum which he said that he would support before the Minister of Finance.
                    He added that the question possessed broad political aspects which financial
                    authorities were inclined to overlook and declared that the conclusion of an
                    agreement of even very limited range would yet constitute an opening and helpful
                    wedge for further mutual concessions.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Weddell</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
